{When partner opens 1NT, interference can easily gum up your smooth bidding sequences. Playing the lebensohl convention, your 3\H bid shows a 5-card suit and is forcing to game.

It doesn't always work out so well, but here partner had an easy 4\H bid.

North plays 4\H. East leads the \ST.

Whatever you play, West takes the \S A K J and then plays a small \C. East started with just one \S.

Loser List: \S = 3 : \H = ? : \D = 0 : \C = 0 :: Total = ?

Don't let that Question Mark by the \H losers mislead you - if you are going to make this contract you cannot lose a \H trick at all! Is there any hope? 

The odds aren't good, but you actually have <b>TWO</b> possibilities for success. If East holds the singleton \HK, you can play a small \H to dummy's \HA, dropping the \HK, then finesse West out of his \HJ. Or, if West holds the singleton \HJ you can play your \HQ, finessing East for the \HK and at the same time smothering West's \HJ.

Which basket will you put your eggs into? 

The answer is simple Bridge math! West started with 6 \Ss leaving him 7 cards outside the \S suit. East started with just 1 \S, leaving him with 12 cards outside the \S suit. Obviously West is much more likely to have a singleton \H than East.

So you win the \CA in your hand, play the \HQ and let it ride if East does not cover.

Then you  

Ahh, success.

But to tell the truth, the Bridge math wasn't really complete. Distribution-wise it was just fine, but there is also the question of strength.

The fact that West overcalled makes it more likely that he holds more high cards than East, and this skews the odds toward West holding the \HK.

But think about it. If West does in fact hold the singleton \HK, and if you cleverly drop it by playing dummy's \HA it won't help you. You will then have to lose a trick to East's \HJ.}
[Play "W"]ST

