{With 12 points and a 4-card Major suit you automatically use Stayman; bid 2\C. Partner responds 2\D.  

With 12 points and a 4-card Major suit you automatically use Stayman; bid 2\C. Partner responds 2\D. 

You have plenty of points for game; with no 4-4 Major suit fit you bid 3NT.

The contract would be 3NT played by South.

North plays 3NT. East leads the \H6.

First big decision. Which \H do you play from dummy?

Winner List: \S = 2 : \H = 1 : \D = 3 : \C = 2 :: Total = 8

The Rule of Eleven tells you there are 5 \Hs in South, West and North which are higher than the \H6. You and dummy hold 4 of them so you can place West with just 1. The missing high cards are \H A J 10 9. Elementary, Watson; West must hold the \H10 because from \H A J 10 6, \H A 10 9 6 or \H J 10 9 6 East would <b>NOT</b> have led the \H6. So your first smart move is to play dummy's \HQ, which holds the trick. What next? 

You need to find one more winner and your best chance is the \C suit. You will need a 3-2 split in the suit, but you must establish the \C winner without letting West get the lead. West is the Danger Hand because he can play a \H throughyour \H K 7. Therefore it would be unwise to play \CA, \CK, then another \C because West is very likely to be the one with 3 \Cs. 

Did you get it? Play a small \C toward your hand and put on the \CT if West plays low. You don't expect the \CT to win the trick, it is more of a duck than a finesse. East takes this with his \CJ but he can do you no harm. If he continues with \Hs your \HK will be a second stopper. If he plays any other suit you will scamper home with your 9 tricks, which of course now include those 3 \Cs.

A duck into the safe hand allowed you to establish the \C winner you needed.

But what if West had figured out what you were going to try and played his \CQ when you led from dummy?

He would have been very, very sorry. You would have had no choice but to win the trick, and when East's \CJ fell on the next trick you would have all 4 \C tricks!}
[Play "W"]H6

